{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T16-43-16-429Z","slug":"the-unassuming-power-of-multiple-choice-questions","locale":"ru","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T16:43:22.554Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2025-01-01--the-unassuming-power-of-multiple-choice-questions/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2025-01-01--the-unassuming-power-of-multiple-choice-questions/ru/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/the-unassuming-power-of-multiple-choice-questions/ru/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T16-43-16-429Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"caa10164f80350a5733ad5c3d7edf12b50afa0765cd3d9f8fd3c5758259550be","outputHash":"e2ec33f2058861467cb6fddff0666dab8b6f187c3b0f3552f47cd4967cc24e25","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The articleargues that well‑crafted multiple‑choice questions are a powerful teaching tool, not just a cheap assessment method. By designing distractors that embody common misconceptions—such as legacy syntax, cross‑platform habits, or edge‑case misunderstandings—the question itself reveals learners’ mental models and reinforces the lesson before any explanation is given. The author illustrates this with a PostgreSQL identity‑column quiz that simultaneously serves beginners, intermediates, and experts, showing how each wrong answer triggers a distinct teaching moment. The piece is aimed at educators, technical writers, and quiz creators who want to improve instructional clarity, and it adopts an analytical, tutorial‑style tone that repeatedly frames MCQs as “curriculum‑building” rather than filler.","totalInputTokens":5731,"totalOutputTokens":1333,"totalCacheReadTokens":1024,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":5019,"totalCostUsd":0.00046344899999999995,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","chunkSize":"6p","totalChunks":6,"totalInputTokens":5731,"total